It is just very hard to read one line all the way across the page. My eyes crossed over to other lines.
It would be good if you can expand on the drug when clicked, instead of having them all listed as such.
having to click through things was very cumbersome.
I guess I'm simply curious as to how this differs, functionally, from what already exists in Maestro? Perhaps explaining that in the intro would increase users' confidence in the tool.

It would be better if medications were categorized according to which chronic condition they were prescribed for. You could click on the chronic condition, and then see the medications that had been prescribed.

This would have been great if you could sort by the various columns.  If I want to see what blood pressure medicine was prescribed first, I should be able to sort by start date, not have to scroll through the entire medication list to pick out BP drugs and compare start dates while keeping them in my head.  Other than the lack of sorting, it was very straightforward and easy to use.
I disliked having to click each entry to see if a medication was filled. I would prefer to be able to down arrow through the list and see the same information.
This last question section, I accidentally clicked the wrong answer and I couldn't go back and change it.
thanks for making the one EMR that could make me feel grateful for Epic
Very easy to use! I imagine it would become more complicated as different variables were added but good stuff overall :)
Need to have the option to be able to sort other columns, not just alphabetically.  For instance, would have liked to be able to sort by prescribed date, sort by prescriber, etc.
It would be great to have color coding when drugs were filled or not (green versus red).

This interface is clear and user-friendly but not especially efficient. The ability to sort/rearrange the medications by column would be useful (date, prescriber, name, and so on), as would a text search box. Alternatively, repeated prescriptions for each medication could be collapsed into expandable sub-menus, for a easier but still more organized implementation. Finally, the ability to compare prescriptions side by side would be helpful.

A few more columns with additional information available would be nice, to avoid having to click on small rows to get a specific medication. Also, it might be nice to have tabs at the top for each medication, or one main row for each medication, and then within either of those options the prescriptions ranging from most recent to oldest. This would alleviate having to repeatedly scroll up and down a long list and look closely at the dates to see which one you want to click on. Finally, some additional drug information on the info box when you click on a prescription would be nice - maybe a free text box for why it was prescribed, dose changed, etc.
So much redundant information in the table. Really hard to pick up changes and any time sequence.
Well laid out application. Ability to sort by dates would also be useful.

It would have been helpful to be able to sort by other columns, such as date or provider.  It would have also been good if there had been a different type of dividing line between medications. Since the "filled" was so important, it should maybe be a column of its own. Although I was confused because if there was 11 refills, there was just one "filled."  I could easily see someone missing 1 month but taking all the other months.

The listing of the medications with date ranges for each individual prescription was a bit difficult to use.  It might be easier if there was a way to list each change in medication as a line with a box for prescriptions issued and a box for prescriptions filled that when you clicked on these boxes you could see a list of the exact prescription issue dates in each category (for the filled box each should be listed with filled or not filled for ease of comparison). That is the only real suggestion.  Otherwise maybe just include some prescription information on the info tab (like what the item was prescribed for).  For example, Naproxen could be prescribed for a diversity of conditions.
I would like to be able to sort by different columns in the final version of this app. For example, sorting by date would allow me to see all of the most recently prescribed medications first.

Not being able to sort medications by date or provider was a frustrating part. Additionally I had a difficult time judging patient compliance based on # of refills vs start date and end dates not matching up.
I loved the organization. It would be great to also be able to reorganize/reorder the list based on current medications only.

This application is significantly improved over the current medication display in Epic. One issue I ran into is that a lot of the questions were about drugs prescribed for particular conditions, and there was no clear way to identify an indication within this display. Also, I would like it if you could minimize and expand the different medications so that you don't have to scroll through 20 lisinopril entries. You end up missing one-time meds. I would also like it if the current drugs were more clearly identified, as by a different color, or something like that.

This display looks great.  It would be nice to have either a tab or symbols indicating which meds the patients is currently taking in that current list.  (i.e. a symbol next to his current prescription for metformin)

Put reasons for adding or discontinuing a medication into the little pop up boxes that come up when you click on a medication. also I couldn't listen to the tutorial with sound so I think that made this a little more difficult for me

I think that when items in a column are duplicated, it is unnecessary to show all of them listed out in each row.  Rather, it would be both easier on the eyes as well as easier to find things if you showed only when medications were changed.  For instance, you could have an arrow pointing downward to imply that additional rows reflect what is in the row above them.  I also would like it if when I clicked on a row, that row would remain highlighted kind of as a placeholder so that I could find it again easily.  Including a column for whether or not something was filled would also speed things up so that I would have to do less guessing and clicking.  Grouping drugs in similar medication classes with similar colors would be a cool improvement.

What frustrated me to no end with this EMR set up was that it seemed to change layout on different platforms.  I first tried to do the survey on my ipad, and the tutorial instructed me on how to use the EMR in a color-coded horizontal layout, which seemed intuitive and easy to use.  The only problem was that on my ipad, the layout cut off either ends of the screen, so that I couldn't see or answer the clinical questions on the left.  Then, when I logged in to my computer to complete the survey, the EMR was in a completely different layout.  Everything was essentially the same color and vertical.  After seeing the previous format, I had a strong dislike of the one I eventually had to use to answer the clinical questions.  It greatly increased my frustration and I ended the exercise feeling downright angry.
